olarship Stoller argues for the importance of understanding the "sensuous epistemologies" of many non-Western societies so that we can better understand the societies themselves and what their epistemologies have to teach us about human experience in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEthnologievPhilosophie. 0aEthnologyvMethodology. 0aEthnologyvPhilosophy. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvAnthropologyvGeneral. 0aSensuality. 0aSonghai (African people)vReligion. 0aSonghai (African people)vSocial conditions. 0aSonghai (African people)xHistory. 0aSonghai (African people)xReligion. 4aAnthropology. 4aFolklore. 4aLinguistics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220313440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812203134.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041361-8  Penn Press eBook Package Social Sciences  a978-3-11-044252-6  Penn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK